## 10.10.2025 Family Dinneroo WBR \- Week 6

Author(s)/Contributor(s): [Abi Horner](mailto:abi.horner@deliveroo.co.uk) [Nico Phillpott](mailto:nicholas.phillpott@deliveroo.com.au)[Chloe Morgan](mailto:chloe.morgan@deliveroo.co.uk)[Johanne Soeun Chu](mailto:johanne.chu@deliveroo.com)[Iain Willmore](mailto:iain.willmore@deliveroo.co.uk)[Iona Cameron](mailto:iona.cameron@deliveroo.co.uk)[Simon Jones](mailto:simon.jones@deliveroo.co.uk)[Chloe Hobson](mailto:chloe.hobson@deliveroo.co.uk)[James Barnes](mailto:james.barnes@deliveroo.co.uk)[Lina Gallego](mailto:lina.gallego@deliveroo.co.uk)[Leon Man](mailto:leon.man@deliveroo.co.uk)[Sheena Kotadia](mailto:sheena.kotadia@deliveroo.co.uk)

Date: 10 Oct 2025  
***Follow up actions added to [8\. Follow-ups](#bookmark=id.fufzs0gocddw)***

### Summary

**Overall OV has seen only a slight uptick vs last week** (3,563 delivered W6 vs 3,546 W5) despite the marketing launch

* A time lag is expected before marketing impact fully materialises.  
* In addition, a few counteracting factors this week may have limited uplift: (i) Home carousel experiment ended (as planned), (ii) Braze marketing pop up stopped running (as planned), (iii) Merch card reached its impression cap for some users, causing it to disappear from their view.

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=id.8jy7lqj4zkht) **No major changes in proposition performance vs previous weeks** *\[W6 figs shown; W1-5 figs included only where they differ meaningfully\]*

* **Order Composition**  
  * **Ordering Patterns:** Order volumes rise through the week, peaking on Wednesday or Thursday. ASAP orders make up 81% of total, while scheduled orders account for 19% \- up from 16% W1-5. For ASAP orders, volumes build over the 4:30-6:30pm slot, peaking at 6:15-6:30pm (21%). Most scheduled orders are placed on the same day (92% \- up from 83% W1-5), with a concentration between 4:00-4:30pm (24%).  
  * **Top performing brands:** The proposition is highly concentrated among the leading brands \- the top 5 account for 67% of OV (vs a forecast of 64%). The leading FTT brands are Pho (21%), Wags (17%), Dishoom (13%), PEX (11%) Banana Tree (9%) and Bills (6%). Based on overall GTV performance, the forecasted top brands were Wags (26%), Kokoro (12%), PEX (11%), Pho (9%), Dishoom (6%). This suggests a partial alignment between total GTV and FTT-specific performance. However, Pho, Dishoom, Banana Tree, and Bill‚Äôs are outperforming in FTT \- likely due to their broader family appeal \- while Wags, Kokoro and PEX are performing in line with or slightly below expectations.  
  * **Top performing cuisines:** Asian cuisine leads, followed by Indian, Italian, and British. This indicates that brand strength is a stronger driver of choice than cuisine type \- as consumer research had suggested Italian and British would dominate.  
  * **Top performing dishes:** Wags Family Chicken Katsu continues to be the most popular dish (13% OV) followed by Pho‚Äôs Pho the Whole Family (12%), Dishoom‚Äôs Chicken Ruby (7%), Banana Tree‚Äôs Mix n Match Rice Bowl (6%) and Pho‚Äôs It‚Äôs a curry night (5%).  
* **Cx Composition**  
  * **Families:** Consumer survey suggests [54%](#a\)-consumer-insights-\(simon-jones,-francesca-mcgovern\)) of customers are families (significantly higher than LBDS estimates (16%)). Driven by Wags (68% families), Itsu (65%), PEX (65%), Pho (57%), Bill's (57%). Those attracting lower percentage of families are Banana Tree (41%) and Dishoom (38%); (Low response rates, but) Farmer J, Bella and Kricket may be attracting as low as ‚Öì families.   
  * **New vs Existing Cx:** Majority of cx (99%) are existing vs new-to-platform.  
  * **PLUS:** FTT cx over index on being PLUS members \- 66% are PLUS members.  
  * **Location:** FTT OV composition by region closely aligns to total Roo GTV composition by region, over indexing slightly in the South and under indexing in CL \- FTT split is 34% CL, 30% GL, 23% SEW, 9% North, 5% I\&S; overall GTV split (FTT zones only) is 39% CL, 30% GL, 16% SEW, 9% North, 7% I\&S.  
* **Cx Behaviour**  
  * (i) The number of cxs reached and converted (ii) cx segmentation into new-to-FTT vs returning-to-FTT and (iii) cx new-to-rx split to be updated following the WBR as the snowflake boostable warehouse has been unavailable today.

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=id.e47f0rcxdspk) ‚ÄòHard launched‚Äô this week with DXGY, Digital Audio, OOH and YouTube/Meta live from 6/10, Hero Talent content talent channels (8/10) on Sky AdSmart, BVOD and YouTube **went live earlier than planned 9/10**. Next week more organic & paid influencers, and hero talent on YouTube/Meta to go live.

**DXGY**: Successful launch operationally, but early days on performance and metrics need time to mature. 2.3k Cx have entered, 4.3% of those have placed their second order with five Cx completing all steps, and 1 of these having spent their voucher. As a result, spend to date is ¬£25.

Too early to review broader media / brand KPI impact. On CRM and Digital Marketing:

* CRM: CTR on both emails and push is declining (email 0.1% vs 0.3% previous weeks, push 0.5% vs 0.6%); set of actions planned to address this.  
* Search: 506 attributed orders from search; CTR below Rx benchmarks 1.63% (vs. avg CTR 8.37% Rx campaigns); set of actions underway to address this.

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=id.xaawvvkuqgme) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=id.2bly6deyk5rk)*** Slight improvements in service metrics, but similar challenges persist

* **B10s:** Continue to be elevated vs Non-Dinneroo (11.87%) \- though slight fall WoW (-0.76 ppt) driven by unacceptable lates decreasing (-0.81 ppt to 7.79%). RWT has continued to decrease for the 7th week in a row \-0.80 ppt to 7.7% (lowest yet but 2.8 ppt above Non-Dinneroo rate of 4.9%). For the first time OI has increased \+0.02 ppt to 2.86% (+0.73 ppt above non-Dinneroo OI rate of 2.13%) \- most common issues continue to be: missing items or components, spillage & packaging failures, wrong or incorrect items and poor food quality & cooking issues. 10 partners have been flagged for a disproportionately high number of RWT or OI issues compared to their non-Dinneroo orders, with follow-up actions underway.  
* **Claims:** Similar vs last week with claims at 6.52% (-0.04 ppt) and average claim amount at ¬£13.76 (+¬£0.52).  
* **OTP:** OTP is 36p per Dinneroo order, which is \+26p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit) (10p) and \+15p above budget (21p).  
* **Cx ratings:** Ratings slightly up (4.5 vs 4.4 W1-5), with majority 5\* (77% up from 73% W1-5). Key feedback received ([Cx Survey](#a\)-consumer-insights-\(simon-jones,-francesca-mcgovern\))):  
  * **Menu Accuracy**: Across the board, dish photography needs to catch up to menu descriptions in terms of perceived accuracy. Dishoom, Kricket and Bills are setting the gold standard for image accuracy.  
  * **Portion sizes**: Families are more critical than non-families. Wagamamas and Las Iguanas may need to catch up to the rest on their portions.   
  * **Packaging & Spillage**: Broadly consistent positivity with the big players around packaging and spoilage üëèüëè. PEX, Farmer J and Kricket have most concerns.  
  * **Kid-Friendliness:** Kids are struggling most with dishes from Dishoom, Banana Tree, Pho and Itsu making families less likely to order again from these brands (Dishoom appears to be an exception here).

#### B) CRM & Digital Marketing Performance Insights ([Lina Gallego](mailto:lina.gallego@deliveroo.co.uk)[Leon Man](mailto:leon.man@deliveroo.co.uk) ) 

**CRM:**   
In week 5 we launched FT for IRE and included new FT zones in the UK. Additionally, starting in Week 6, we launched the Family Dinneroo rewards (DoXgetY) journey ([Creatives](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1eiWAcwP1mJ7eV9R-cw0CcxYJ2f_4i7YGR3r52oKUuyI/edit?slide=id.g387d76168f2_0_33#slide=id.g387d76168f2_0_33)).  For week 5/6, we are seeing a trend of declining CTR for both email and push (CTR for email 0.1% vs 0.3% of previous weeks, CTR for push 0.5% vs 0.6% of previous weeks). We are launching some proactive actions from next week (see below), and we will monitor Cx engagement with FT communications in the next 2 weeks to see if we need to propose additional changes. 

Actions for next week:

* Tighten targeting further \- we had limited targeting to active Cx and Cx who had opened FT communications, from next week we will limit targeting to only active Cx.   
* We are sending communications at the most impactful times to drive CTR (email 12.30, push 4.30) \- see XP results below  
* We are testing day of the week to understand which day of the week drives higher conversion from our FT Cx.   
* Monitoring best performing emails \- next week we are launching again our Great Brands FT email/push which had the strongest performance to date (CTR \~0.7% vs 0.3%). We will monitor week 7 results to see if we observe similarly high engagement, and evaluate if it makes sense to use this asset more.   
* Keep an eye on new vs returning Cx \- One of our hypotheses is that Cx might be getting fatigued from FT communications. Looking at engagement of both of these Cx types in week 5 we see new Cx having a higher engagement in email (0.4% vs 0.3% average) and push (0.9% vs 0.5% average)

We received results from our week 4 time of day XP. In this experiment we tested sending email and push @8:00 am, @12:30pm, and @4:00 pm. 

* For **email**, the 12:30pm send drove the highest CTR% and orders across both Great Brands and Family Time (CTR \~ 0.8%)  
* For **push**, the 4:30pm send performed best (CTR \~ 1.9% GB, 0.6% FT)

We have already adjusted the timing of this week 6 send to the above.

**Search:**  
MTD search has delivered 308,254 impressions, resulting in 5,104 clicks and 506 attributed orders. **CTR stands at 1.63% (vs. avg CTR 8.37% Rx campaigns)** & a total spend to date of ¬£11,447.

We‚Äôve made adjustments to the search strategy with a focus on improving relevancy and engagement. Specifically, we have refined keyword targeting by shifting from broad match to exact and phrase match types. This change has increased CTR by 0.06% and addressed the issue of overly broad search terms that previously drove lower CTR. By concentrating on delivery related and branded terms (e.g., ‚ÄúDinneroo‚Äù), as well as tighter keyword control, we expect to see stronger alignment between user intent and ad messaging, however, spend will be restricted. This should in turn help improve CTR and overall campaign efficiency.

| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Sept 1st-Oct 7th**  | 308254 | 5014 | 1.63% | ¬£11447 | 506 |

**Key Operating Theatre Takeaways**  
Challenges Remaining: 

* Operational Performance \- a number of partners continue to be re-offenders with little improvement, such as Farmer J (OI & RWT), Pizza Express (RWT), Dishoom (RWT), TUK TUK (RWT) and Prezzo (OI). More detail below.   
* Proposition \- Giggling Squid portion sizes remain a consistent detractor for customers and Prezzo‚Äôs proposition is not driving OV and they have poor ops performance

#### B) Operational Challenges ([Iain Willmore](mailto:iain.willmore@deliveroo.co.uk)[Vandana Prashar](mailto:vandana.prashar@deliveroo.co.uk))

B10s continue to be elevated vs. Non-Dinneroo mealtimes; B10s have decreased WoW (-0.76 ppt WoW to 11.87%). This is being driven by unacceptable lates decreasing 0.81 ppt to 7.79%, RWT has continued to decrease for the 7th week in a row \-0.80 ppt to 7.7% (lowest yet but 2.8 ppt above Non-Dinneroo rate of 4.9%). The worst performers with OV above 5 were TUK TUK-SGroup (55.6%), Kokoro (17.4%) and Tiffin Tin (16.7%). Top RWT contributors continue to be Pho (7.2% RWT w/ 24.3% contribution), PizzaExpress (14.7% RWT w/ 19.5% contribution) and Wagamama(5.9% RWT w/ 15.8% contribution). 6/31 brands have elevated RWT % compared to their non-Dinneroo orders from 4PM-7PM. Actions flagged from focus brands from previous week:

This is the first week where we have seen OI increase WoW \+0.02 ppt to 2.86% ( \+0.73 ppt above non-Dinneroo OI rate of 2.13%). The worst performers with OI above 5 were Farmer J (15.71%), The Salad Project (14.29%) and Xian Street Food (7.4%). Top OI contributors continue to be Pho (3.33% OI w/ 41.67% contribution), Wagamama (3.02% OI w/ 30% contribution) and Farmer J (15.71% OI w/ 18.33% contribution). 4/31 brands have elevated OI % compared to their non-Dinneroo orders from 4PM-7PM. Across all partners, the most common issues continue to be:

- **Missing Items or Components:** Entire dishes, sides, sauces, or key garnishes not included. (Farmer J, Pho, Wagamama, Bill's, Kricket, PizzaExpress)  
- **Spillage & Packaging Failures:** Leaked sauces/soups, broken containers, and crushed items. (Pho, Chaska, Banana Tree, Farmer J, Giggling Squid, Las Iguanas, PizzaExpress, Cocotte, Itsu, Xian Street Food)  
- **Wrong or Incorrect Items:** Completely wrong orders, or specific dishes being incorrect (e.g., meat instead of vegetarian). (Pho, Banana Tree, Bill's, Dishoom, Farmer J, PizzaExpress, Cocotte)  
- **Poor Food Quality & Cooking Issues:** Burnt, undercooked, cold, or badly prepared food; portion sizes not matching descriptions. (PizzaExpress, Bill's, Dishoom, Wagamama, Las Iguanas, Giggling Squid, Kricket, Pho, Bella Italia, Iro Sushi, Prezzo)

Px Ops have flagged ten partners with a concerningly high number of OI or RWT  via the ‚ÄòCentralised Px Mobilisation' sheet. AMs have been given details on which B10s are trending in the wrong direction and supported on providing further analysis.  Details for three of those brands are detailed below:

* Bills \- OI increase, RWT decrease. Continued theme with Cx receiving wrong order items, such as Cx receiving shepherds pie, instead of mac and cheese due to packaging being the same, Cx have also called out packaging being flimsy and lid falling off when arriving. AM has discussed with Bills and whilst there is not a quick fix on packaging, Bills have agreed to write on top of all items to reduce missing items and/or wrong items being sent out (they will look into stickers too). Ongoing discussions regarding ‚Äòsquashed‚Äô packaging and if its the way site staff and placing items into bags.  
* Xi‚Äôan Street Food \- OI increase, RWT decrease. Multiple conversations have been had with the partner, but have proven difficult to land messaging that they have the ability to positively impact RWT. Additional resources are being pulled together to investigate prep times and pull data in an effort to reinforce our position and dispel owner's claims. Efforts from Xian to improve ops will be more challenging as the partner on the 9th Oct threatened to breach exclusivity in an effort to secure a lower commission rate. Commercial and Ops are still working on an Ops improvement plan, for the partner, due to be shared by 17th Oct.  
* Farmer J \- OI continuing to increase WoW. The partner is continuing to not engage in discussing issues. Meeting scheduled for Friday with senior management to address this.

* Prezzo \- Orders have been averaging less than 10 orders a week, with an average order rating of 2.4. There are concerns about the menu items being too pasta heavy. In addition to this, their OI is averaging 26%.  

Partners issues continue to be discussed daily on the Operating Theatre call, including root cause, actions taken and any px feedback. The theatre will continue for the foreseeable future.

Scenarios were re-run with updated input metrics to reflect current performance accurately. These revised estimates are for combined ASAP \+ Scheduled orders, and maintain the same estimation assumptions as the original sizing:

* Plus Gold late-order proportion: 17.89%  
* Monthly average OTP claim rate (Plus Diamond/Gold): 47.42%

#### A) Consumer Insights ([Simon Jones](mailto:simon.jones@deliveroo.co.uk), [Francesca McGovern](mailto:francesca.mcgovern@deliveroo.co.uk)) {#a)-consumer-insights-(simon-jones,-francesca-mcgovern)}

* ### **Daily CX survey to all Cx who used Dinneroo the previous day and didn‚Äôt rate 1-2 stars** (must have opted into marketing). [Weekly data sheet here](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1LQHlJ1ojViIuga3tfSpHYca7SvxkncstqsmeeCO2zS8/edit?gid=1169824723#gid=1169824723), updated daily.

  * *Decision needed:* 5 weeks completed so far, but we need to roll back as it‚Äôs a heavy resource lift. 2 proposals:  
    * 1\. **Stop completely**, focus on families analysis (500 responses)  
    * 2\. **Shift to weekly** for the next month (to monitor)

* Partner-level analysis  
  * *Decision needed*: Who needs to see this aggregated data? (who / how / when)  
      
  * **Families**  
* **54%** of orders are from families.   
  * This is concentrated in a few key partners like **Wagamama**, **Pho**, **Pizza** **Express** & **Bills**.   
  * **Dishoom**, **Banana Tree**, **Farmer J**, **Bella Italia** and **Kricket** are attracting the lowest portion of families. 

    ![][image1]

* **The key success factor is the 'kid test'. 76% of kids were full and happy, leaving 24% of kids unsatisfied.**   
  * For families, if the kids aren‚Äôt happy with the food, this correlates with their likelihood of reordering the same dish again.   
  * Kids are struggling most with dishes from **Dishoom**, **Banana Tree**, **Pho** and **Itsu**.   
    * As a result, families are less likely to order from **Banana Tree**, **Pho** and **Itsu** again.   
    * **Dishoom** is the exception, which may have staying power potentially because of brand trust/premium perception.  
      ![][image2]![][image3]

        
* There‚Äôs no evidence yet that partners are damaging the overall proposition. Families typically remain **open to trying a different Dinneroo restaurant**, even after a **disappointing first experience**.

  ![][image4]

  * **Portion Sizes**  
* **Families** are more critical on portion sizes.   
  * **Wagamamas** and **Las Iguanas** may need to catch up to the rest of their portions.   
* Low incidence numbers, **Giggling Squid**, are generating **negative sentiment** with their portion size for families.

  ![][image5]

  * **Menus and Operations**  
* There is a gap between our **food photography** and the delivered product across all partners, which needs to be addressed.   
  * **Dishoom**, **Kricket** and **Bills** may be setting the gold standard for photography, while others feel less reflective of what arrived.

    ![][image6]

* Broadly consistent positivity with the big players around **packaging** and **spoilage**  üëèüëè   
  * **PEX** and **Kricket** have the biggest concerns around spoilage.
